  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-3", "C1) after 19...Qf6", "r4rk1/2p2ppp/p1B2q2/1p6/1b1P4/1P2P1P1/1B2QP1P/R4K2 w - - 1 20"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-4", "C2) after 14...Ra7", "3q1rk1/r1pbbppp/p1n1p3/1p6/3P4/1PB1PNP1/4QPBP/R1R3K1 w - - 1 15"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-5", "135  1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.g3 d5 4.Nf3 dxc4 5.Bg2 a6 6.0-0 Nc6  This is an ambitious choice from Black. In most of the lines he will retain his extra pawn, but White has a few interesting ways to fight for the initiative.", "r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1n1pn2/8/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 7"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-6", "Other squares are much worse:  8...Ndb4? 9.Be3 Bd6 10.a3 Nd3 occurred in Weiler – Grzeca, Altenkirchen 2012, and now White could have obtained a huge advantage with:", "r1bqk2r/1pp2ppp/p1nbp3/8/2pPP3/P2nBNP1/1P3PBP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 1 11"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-7", "11.Qc2N b5 12.e5 Be7 13.b3! It is hard to suggest anything for Black. A possible continuation is 13...Na5 14.bxc4 bxc4 15.Nfd2! Rb8 16.Nxc4 Nxc4 17.Qxc4 Nb2 18.Qc2 and Black’s knight is in big trouble.  8...Nf6 9.Nc3 b5 (Other moves allow White to regain the pawn, for example 9...Be7 10.Qa4 Bd7 11.Qxc4 0-0 12.Rd1 b5 13.Qe2 with a comfortable edge, Kachiani – Burtman, Azov 1990.) 10.d5 Nb4", "r1bqkb1r/2p2ppp/p3pn2/1p1P4/1np1P3/2N2NP1/PP3PBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 11"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-8", "Beneficially opening up the a-file.  11...exd5 (After 11...Rb8N 12.axb5 axb5 13.Bg5 Be7 14.Nd4 White’s initiative plays itself.) Now in a couple of games White failed to find 12.axb5!N when Black is in serious trouble. For instance, 12...Be7 13.e5 Ne4 14.Nd4! Bb7 15.Nf5→ with an almost decisive initiative.", "r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/pnn1p3/8/2pPP3/5NP1/PP3PBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-9", "Position", "1rbqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1n1pn2/8/2pP4/4PNP1/PP3PBP/RNBQ1RK1 w k - 1 8"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-10", "8.Qe2 b5 9.b3 cxb3 10.axb3 is an interesting alternative, but it gives Black a better version of variation C below, since his light-squared bishop can be developed comfortably to b7.  Here the two main options are B1) 8...Qd7 and B2) 8...e5.  8...Bd7 9.Nxc4 b5 works out well for White after 10.Ne5! Nxe5 11.dxe5 Nd5 as in Le Quang – Ponkratov, Moscow 2013. Here White should just continue with normal development as follows:", "1r1qkb1r/2pb1ppp/p3p3/1p1nP3/8/4P1P1/PP3PBP/RNBQ1RK1 w k - 1 12"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-11", "Position", "1rb1kb1r/2pq1ppp/p1n1pn2/1p6/3P4/4P1P1/PP1N1PBP/RNBQ1RK1 b k - 1 10"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-12", "This has been Black’s choice in games featuring the other moves mentioned above, but it does not work so well here. I also considered:  11...e5 proves to be premature after 12.d5 Nd8 13.e4 c6 14.Bg5, when Black is not ready for such a tense clash in the centre, since his king is still uncastled.  11...Bd6 also does not work well after 12.e4 e5 13.dxe5 Bxe5 14.Nc5! Qxd1 15.Rxd1 Bc8 16.Nc3 0-0 17.Be3 with an unpleasant endgame for Black.  Finally, 11...a5 runs into 12.a4! bxa4 13.Rxa4 Bb4 14.Bd2 when the a5-pawn is a clear target. The continuation might be:", "1r2k2r/1bpq1ppp/2n1pn2/p7/Rb1P4/1N2P1P1/1P1B1PBP/1N1Q1RK1 b k - 2 14"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-13", "14...Nd8 15.Nxa5 Bxa5 16.Rxa5 Bxg2 17.Kxg2 Rxb2 18.Qc1 Rb8 19.Qa3  Despite the simplifications, Black is a long way from solving his problems.", "1r1nkb1r/1bpq1ppp/p3pn2/1p6/3P4/1N2P1P1/PP3PBP/RNBQ1RK1 w k - 4 12"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-14", "Position", "1r1nkb1r/1bpq1pp1/p3pn2/1p6/3PP1P1/1N3P1p/PP5P/RNBQ1RKB b k - 1 15"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-15", "Position", "1rbqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p1n2n2/4p3/2pP4/4P1P1/PP1N1PBP/RNBQ1RK1 w k - 0 9"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-16", "Other options are clearly worse:  11...Qd5? 12.b3 Qe6 13.f4 Qh6 14.Qe2 Bc5 15.Ba3± Zaichik – Anikaev, Telavi 1982.  11...Qxd1 12.Rxd1 Be6 13.Nbd2 Rd8 14.b3  White maintains a comfortable edge in the endgame, for instance:  14...Bxc4 15.bxc4 Bb4 16.Rb1 c5  Another game continued 16...Ba5 17.Kf1! 0-0 (17...Nxh2+ 18.Ke2 Ng4 19.Rb7 Bxd2 20.Bxd2 0-0 21.f4±) 18.Ke2 Bxd2 19.Bxd2 Nxe5 20.Be1!? with a nice edge for White, Lissang – Welin, Sweden 2007.  17.h3 Nxe5 18.Bb2 Nc6 19.Nb3 0-0", "3r1rk1/2p2ppp/p1n5/2p5/1bP5/1N2P1PP/PB3P2/1R1R2K1 w - - 4 20"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-17", "From this position Black’s two main ideas are B21) 12...h5 and B22) 12...Bb4.  12...Qd5 13.b3 h5 was Carlhammar – Schneider, Helsingborg 1991. Now I believe White could have simply played:", "1r2kb1r/2p2pp1/p1p1b3/3qP2p/2N3n1/1P2P1P1/P2N1P1P/R1BQ1RK1 w k - 0 14"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-18", "Position", "1r1qkb1r/2p2pp1/p1p1b3/4P3/2N3P1/4P1p1/PP1N3P/R1BQ1RK1 w k - 0 15"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-19", "This seems like a better try than 15...Qd3 16.b3 Rxh2 17.Qxg3 Rh6 as played in Postny – A. Mikhalevski, Israel 2009.", "1r2kb2/2p2pp1/p1p1b2r/4P3/2N3P1/1P1qP1Q1/P2N4/R1B2RK1 w - - 1 18"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-20", "Position", "1r1qk2r/2p2ppp/p1p1b3/4P3/1bN3n1/4P1P1/PP1N1P1P/R1BQ1RK1 w k - 3 13"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-21", "140", "1r1qk2r/2p2pp1/p1p1b3/4P3/1bN3n1/1P2PNp1/P1Q2P1P/R1B2RK1 w k - 0 16"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-22", "Position", "r2qkb1r/1ppb1ppp/p1n1pn2/8/2pP4/4PNP1/PP3PBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 8"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-23", "In a number of recent games Black has tried 8...Bd6 9.Qxc4 0-0, returning the pawn and aiming for a quick strike in the centre. I suggest following Gelfand’s example: 10.Rd1 Rb8 11.Nbd2 e5 12.dxe5 Bxe5 (Apparently Black was not satisfied with 12...Nxe5 13.Nxe5 Bxe5 14.Nf3 Bd6 15.e4, when White indeed has good prospects.) 13.Qe2 Qe7 14.Nc4 Rfd8 15.Bd2", "1r1r2k1/1ppbqppp/p1n2n2/4b3/2N5/4PNP1/PP1BQPBP/R2R2K1 b - - 5 15"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-24", "141", "r2qkb1r/2pb1ppp/p1n1pn2/1p6/3P4/1P2PNP1/4QPBP/RNB2RK1 b kq - 0 10"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-25", "This move has only been played in correspondence games, but it is undoubtedly the most logical choice. The following game gives a good illustration of how play may proceed.", "r2q1rk1/2pb1ppp/p1n1p3/1p1n4/1b1P4/1P1NP1P1/1B2QPBP/RN3RK1 b - - 6 13"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-26", "Now in Schiller – Wharrier, email 2012, White rushed to take on a8. A stronger and more thematic option would have been:", "r4rk1/2p2ppp/p1B2q2/1p6/1b1P4/1P2P1P1/1B2QP1P/R4K2 w - - 1 20"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-27", "Position", "r2qk2r/2pbbppp/p1n1pn2/1p6/3P4/1P2PNP1/4QPBP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 1 11"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-28", "I would also like to mention: 12...Ra7 13.Nc3 Nb8 (I also checked 13...Be8!?N, which looks better than the text move. Nevertheless, after 14.Ne1! Nb4 15.Na2! Nxa2 16.Rxa2 Nd5 17.Nd3 White has excellent compensation.) 14.Ne5 Be8", "1n1qbrk1/r1p1bppp/p3pn2/1p2N3/3P4/1PN1P1P1/3BQPBP/R1R3K1 w - - 9 15"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-29", "Intending Nb4 – a strong manoeuvre which is worth remembering.  15...Nd5 16.Qe1!? Bd6 17.Nd3  White was clearly better in D. Berczes – Goloshchapov, Griesheim 2011.", "r2q1rk1/2pbbppp/p1n1p3/1p1n4/3P4/1P2PNP1/3BQPBP/RNR3K1 w - - 5 13"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-30", "This position first occurred in Kachiani Gersinka – Ar. Petrosian, Dortmund 2000, and it has since been repeated numerous times.", "3q1rk1/r1pbbppp/p1n1p3/1p6/3P4/1PB1PNP1/4QPBP/R1R3K1 w - - 1 15"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-31", "143  the game after 18.Qc2 Rc8 19.Bc6!∞ with good positional compensation.", "3q1rk1/r1pb1ppp/p2bp3/1p6/3P4/1P1NP1P1/4QPBP/R1R3K1 w - - 2 18"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-32", "Position", "r2qk2r/2pb1ppp/p1nbpn2/1p6/3P4/1P2PNP1/4QPBP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 1 11"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-33", "14.dxe5N Nd5 15.Nc3 is also great for White.", "r4rk1/2pbqppp/p1B1pn2/1p2b3/3P4/1P2P1P1/1B2QP1P/RNR3K1 b - - 0 14"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-34", "Somehow White went on to lose from this position in Evdokimov – Shinkevich, Ufa 2004. The simplest way to maintain a clear advantage would have been:", "r5k1/2pbqppp/p4n2/1p2b3/8/1P2P1P1/1B1NQP1P/R1R3K1 w - - 0 18"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-35", "13...Nfd5? is no good in view of 14.Nxd7 Qxd7 15.e4 Nb6 16.e5 Be7 17.Bxa8 Rxa8 18.Nd2± when Black does not have enough for the exchange.  13...Ra7 is playable, but 14.Na3 Be8 15.e4∞ gave White great compensation in Bucek – Hnatovsky, Internet 2011.", "2rq1rk1/2pb1ppp/p2bpn2/1p2N3/1n1P4/1P2P1P1/1B2QPBP/RNR3K1 w - - 7 14"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-36", "Position", "3q1rk1/3b1ppp/p3pn2/1pb1N3/1n6/NP2P1P1/1B2QPBP/R5K1 w - - 0 17"),
  sourcePosition("ch10-fen-37", "Position", "r2q1rk1/2pb1ppp/p1nbp3/1p1n4/3P4/1P2PNP1/1B2QPBP/RNR3K1 w - - 5 13")
